    <!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
        <handout margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="Week14Wed">
            <title>Wednesday Week 14 - Limit Calculations and Applications</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Understand function domination formally in terms of limits.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Calculate limits at infinity using algebra and numerical reasoning.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    See how limits are used in justifying a familiar formula.
                </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    One of the fundamental problems in Calculus is to determine the limit as <m>x\to\infty</m> of a function of the form
                    <md>
                        f(x) = \frac{p(x)}{q(x)},
                    </md>
                    where either
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} p(x) = \infty</m> and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} q(x) = \infty</m>, or
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} p(x) = 0</m> and <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty} q(x) = 0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    The first situation answers which of the numerator or denominator dominates. The second situation has other applications (see below). (We also work with limits as <m>x</m> approaches finite values.)
                </p>
            </introduction>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Strategy for Approching Limits</title>
    <p>
        In order to evaluate limits, proceed as follows:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Attempt to just substitute the limit value of <m>x</m> into the expression and see if it makes sense. If it does, this is the limit (unless the function is intentionally broken).
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Do algebra to manipulate the expression into an equivalent expression for which plugging in makes sense.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</paragraphs>

<example>
    
</example>

</page>
<page>


<example><title>Algebraic Limit Calculations</title>


    <statement>
        <p>
            Find the following limits with algebra.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1.75in">
                    <m>\lim\limits_{x\to\infty}\frac{5x^2 + 2x +1}{2x^3 - x^2 + 9}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <em>Hint:</em> Factor out the highest power in the numerator and denominator.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1.75in">
                    <m>\lim\limits_{t\to\infty}\frac{4e^{t} + 3e^{-t}}{5e^{t} + 2e^{-t}}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p workspace="1.75in">
                    <m>\lim\limits_{x\to 3}\frac{x^2 - 9}{x-3}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </statement>


</example>

</page>
<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>A Familiar Formula Using a Limit</title>
<p>
    Inscribe a regular <m>n</m>-gon inside a circle of radius <m>r</m>. Using trigonometry, we can find the area as a function of <m>n</m>. If we let <m>n\to \infty</m> (maybe using technology), we should get the area inside a circle of radius <m>r</m>. Let's do it!
</p>

</paragraphs>   



</page>

        

